  "bib_entries": {
    "146168767": {
      "title": "Psychology in Turkey",
      "abstract": "Abstract Several reviews of the history and development of psychology in Turkey (Acars Bazarans Le Compte, 1980; Tan, 1971; Vassaf, 1987) point to its European origins.' The first Chair of Psychology was established, and the first course in psychology was introduced at Istanbul University as early as 1915 by Anschiitz, one of a number of German professors invited to that university. This was during the last days of the Ottoman Empire, before the establishment of the Turkish Republic in 1923."
    },
    "146324489": {
      "title": "Globalising counselling: Humanistic counselling in Kenya",
      "abstract": "This paper explores the application of a Western, psychologically-based model of counselling and counselling training in contexts where the social and cultural conditions differ from mainstream Western societies. A group of Kenyan trainee counsellors following such a course are interviewed about their experience of training. The interview data are analysed to provide a tentative answer to the question of the appropriateness in a Kenyan cultural milieu of a humanistic counselling training model developed in the UK. It is concluded that such application is possible and desirable, if it is undertaken as shared and respectful learning between trainers and trainees."
    },
    "143068676": {
      "title": "Student counselling in Turkish universities",
      "abstract": "This article presents general information about the history, relevant laws and legislation, present status and anticipated future development in Turkish Universities, as well as the student counselling services within these institutions. Special emphasis is placed upon the perceived understanding of counselling as commonly accepted by the society, students and counsellors. While discussing the present status of Turkish University Counselling Centers, the proposed models, research findings and problems of the centers are documented. As a more specific example, the Middle East Technical University Counselling Center is described with a discussion of some of the drawbacks and recommended changes for the advancement of the center. Finally, suggestions for a culturally relevant model in terms of the nature, components and organisational structure of the system are discussed."
    },
    "68327423": {
      "title": "Counselling in developing countries: Turkey and India as examples",
      "abstract": "Turkey and India are developing countries with unique cultural characteristics. The current state of mental health counseling in Turkey and India necessitates new laws, indigenous approaches, adaptations of culture-sensitive approaches, and research projects to validate such approaches. It is the job of mental health counselors to accomplish such complicated and trying tasks in the absence of social and financial resources."
    },
    "133276236": {
      "title": "The historical development of counselling in Turkey",
      "abstract": "This article presents an overview of the historical development and the current status of counselling in Turkey. While reviewing the historical background of counselling in this country, the crucial steps taken during each of five periods are documented and poin- ted out. Finally, some anticipated future developments and recommendations to improve the present situation in this field are discussed. Located on the continents of both Europe and Asia, Turkey is literally, and in spirit, a bridge between East and West. The Turkish Republic was built on the ashes of the Ottoman Empire in 1923. Since that date, the population of Turkey has increased more than five times, from 12 million to 63 million today. Turkey has undergone a number of social changes in the twentieth century including the transformation of the state from an empire into a republic, a dramatic rise in population, intensive migration from rural areas to urban areas, and changes in the social status and the role of women. These changes have influenced and been influenced by the educational system and have resulted in increasing the educational needs of Turkish society (Demirel, 1991). Different countries, the world over, developed and underdeveloped (or developing), are now adapting counselling, an originally American phenomenon, to assist people to cope with the problems brought about by the social and economic changes in the modern world in which we live (Bojuwoye, 1992). Moracco (1985) states that the societies interested in modernization must also consider support services that enable the trans- ition from traditional to modern society to be completed with as little psychological disruption and alienation as possible. Counselling in Turkey began in the schools as it did in the United States (Kepceoglu, 1986). Turkey has been making efforts to develop a system of counselling in schools for approximately 50 years. These endeavors have grown from the conviction that counselling is a necessary structural element"
    }
  }
}